l did that come from?)  I could swear I read an article somewhere about how the Russians were looking to stop producing Soyuz capsules because they could no longer afford it.  After doing some research though it appears just the inverse is true.  There's an article at the Moscow Times dated December that says Russia will actually ramp up production of its Soyuz line to support a six man ISS crew.  They're also building a tug to boost the orbit of the ISS in the absence of the shuttle.  It appears we don't really need the shuttle anymore for routine operations at the ISS.  Maybe we should just give funds to Russia to maintain the ISS while we work on new launchers.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 2/16/03 3:26:59 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 2049<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/17/03 10:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=182.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Energia to build first commercial space station?</span><hr size=1> I agree.  The US should become a paying user of Soyuz spacecraft which are far cheaper than the shuttle.  Plus the Russians could use the boost economically. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><b